was false.Molefe received the alleged pension fund money in 2016, when
he left Eskom after he was implicated by then-public protector Thuli Madonsela
in suspicious deals between the power utility and the Gupta family.Anton van der Bijl, head of Solidarity’s Centre for Fair
Labour Practices said on Wednesday that Molefe acted unlawfully and was in no way
within the framework of Eskom’s pension and provident fund.Solidarity approached the high court on November 29 2017 to
declare Molefe's controversial pension award of about R30m, as well as the more
than R10m already paid out to him, unlawful.Molefe’s laywer Barry Farber said the ruling came down like
a ton of bricks, adding that Molefe would be disappointed with it.